<div class="container-fluid aha-header">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
      <h1 class="text-center">American Heart Association:<br>A Usability Study</h1>
      <h3 class="text-center">The Story of a Modern Medical Journalist</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid aha-subheader">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
      <h6 class="text-center">User Research: Getting to Know Medical Journalists</h6>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid aha-project">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-lg-4 col-lg-offset-1">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('aha-persona.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Medical Journalist Persona, Russell</h5>
          <p>1 of 2 data-based personas, Russell's goals and frustrations helped guide the usability testing. His data is a synthesis of 7 interviews of participants from the medical and journalism fields.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-0 col-lg-6">
      <h3>Interviews and Synthesis</h3>
      <h6>Taking Notes at a Medical Conference: It's difficult if you can't find the room.</h6>
      <p>The American Heart Association (AHA) maintains an intranet site for journalists covering the AHA conference, Scientific Sessions. With late-breaking news releases, media briefings, and tightly scheduled interviews, medical conferences can create time constraints for journalists. Quick access to resources is essential.
      <p>With AHA requesting a review of the site, the 6 member usability team found participants from the medical and journalism fields to find out some answers, like:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>What would they use an intranet site for?</li>
        <li>Would they use it before, during, and after the conference?</li> 
        <li>On what device?</li>
        <li>How are they doing research and taking notes?</li>
        <li>Are they having fun or is it stressful?</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The responses and insights from the interviews were organized, analyzed, and synthesized into two personas.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

  <div class="container-fluid aha-conclusions">
    <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h6>The Tool of Data-Based Personas</h6>
      <p>With User Research, I learned that covering a medical conference can make for a busy and challenging day for a journalist. By synthesizing the interview responses into personas with bios, goals, frustrations, and motiviations, I now had an impactful tool to inform and guide the heuristic evaluation, card sort, and scenario-based usability testing for the Scientific Sessions site.</p>
      <p></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  
<div class="container-fluid aha-subheader">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
      <h6 class="text-center">Planning a Card Sort: Information Archictecture and Thinking Like a Journalist</h6>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid aha-project">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-4 col-md-offset-0 col-lg-4">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('database-iteration1.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Database Iteration One</h5>
          <p>Using object-relational mapping, I created models from my client's data to better understand how the data would be used in a Model, View, and Controller framework (MVC).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-4 col-md-offset-0 col-lg-4">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('database-iteration2.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Database Iteration Three</h5>
          <p>Collaborating with techCorp clients, I realized the document object and its characteristics would remain constant and future metadata associations might be needed.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-4 col-md-offset-0 col-lg-4">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('database-schema.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Final Database Schema</h5>
          <p>Working with a PostgreSQL database, the document object was created as the model, <strong>corpus_entry</strong>, which included characteristics of the student, professor, and class.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h3>Database Design</h3>
      <h6>Choosing the Right Tools</h6>
      <p>Using notepads, Visio, and the method of object-relational mapping, I created a database schema that would operate quickly in a MVC framework. Essential to the client, the database would offer flexibility for additional models and growth.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid aha-conclusions">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h6>The Final Database Schema</h6>
      <p>Using Ruby on Rails, a web application framework, I began developing the back-end of techCorp using the reliable and secure Heroku Postgres database. Cloud storage was provided by the Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3).</p>
      <p>After successful testing of the model and data with the CRUD process (create, read, update, and delete), further web development on the back and front-end could begin.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid aha-subheader">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
      <h6 class="text-center">Web Development: Users and Uploads</h6>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid aha-project">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-md-offset-1">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('tc-sign-in.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Creating Users - Iteration One</h5>
          <p>Using the MVC authentication solution, Devise for Rails, the web application would allow users to sign up and upload a document.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-md-offset-0">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('tc-share.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Creating Users - Final Iteration</h5>
          <p>With clear options and instructions, the sign-up page was given the name <strong>Share</strong>, a likeable word that fits the core theme of the corpus.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-md-offset-1 web-copy">
      <h3>Creating Users and Permissions</h3>
      <h6>A Database of Users</h6>
      <p>Using the Devise authentication service, the web application prototype can register users, develop a contact list, and potentially reach out to researchers, professors, and students with incentives and updates.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-md-offset-0 web-copy">
      <h3>Uploading a Document</h3>
      <h6>Interacting with Users</h6>
      <p>I developed the form with the guidance of usability principles and user-feedback. Using think-aloud testing, participants helped guide the order and structure of the form fields. For instance, select options were used to help the user quickly and confidently make entries.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-md-offset-1">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('form-mockup.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Building the Form</h5>
          <p>Understanding how best to organize and group the fields of the form, mockups and user-testing were both utilized. Participants included both students and techCorp clients.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-5 col-md-offset-0">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('tc-form.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>A User-tested Design</h5>
          <p>The Corpus Entry form was divided into three sections with the upload document button positioned last, allowing the user to experience the data and document file as simultaneously saved.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid aha-conclusions">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h6>User-centered Web Development</h6>
      <p>With the needs of the client and user driving the development, the points of interaction with the end-user became the highest priorities, such as:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Ease of use,</li>
        <li>Confidence in the system,</li>
        <li>A responsive design, and</li>
        <li>User-friendly copy.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The listed priorities were accomplished with both web technologies and user feedback. The MVC framework allowed for rapid uploads, Devise authentication created security for the user, Bootstrap structured a mobile-friendly responsive design, and user-feedback benefited the structure, organization, and experience of uploading a document to the corpus.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid aha-subheader">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
      <h6 class="text-center">Designing and Developing the Query Interface</h6>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

