        <%= image_tag('ui-iteration-1.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Interface Iteration One</h5>
          <p>In the mockup of the interface, the ability to easily search through a large corpus would be a guiding priority.</p><br>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-4 col-md-offset-0 col-lg-4">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('tc-explorer.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Interface Iteration Four</h5>
          <p>Collaborating with participants, the sidebar of categories and options was appreciated. The <strong>Genre</strong> option was moved to the top as participants most often used this option to query the corpus.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-4 col-md-offset-0 col-lg-4">
      <div class="thumbnail">
        <%= image_tag('corpus-select-options.png', :class=>'img-responsive') %>
        <div class="caption">
          <h5>Final UI Prototype</h5>
          <p>In the final prototype, a tile format featured essential information and multiple links to the uploaded document.</p><br>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h3>User Interface Design</h3>
      <h6>Speed and the User Experience</h6>
      <p>With modern web technologies and a lightweight design, queries could be performed as quick as under 2 seconds: a primary feature of the user experience. Combined with user-feedback, the user interface was developed and modeled into a familiar, intuitive, and reliable experience for users to access information.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container-fluid aha-conclusions">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-md-6 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-6">
      <h6>The Final Prototype</h6>
      <p>In a trio of services including Ruby on Rails, Heroku, and Amazon Web Services, I produced a lightweight web application that could store and query large masses of data, and with user-feedback and testing, I could ensure techCorp clients that the forms and queries would be reliable to the end-user.</p>
      <p>In preparation for growth, the database schema and architecture was built to encompass large amounts of users, large amounts of data, and the ability to add and merge additional records and associations with the existing data.</p>
      <p>Finally, additional pages were added to the corpus to build trust with the end-user. I included pages such as <strong>About</strong> and <strong>People</strong>, which told the story of the project and its future potential.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

